      "Discounts devalue craft. Here's why SUTRA will never do a 70% off sale and what we do instead.",
    body: `Every brand ambassador I've spoken to gives me the same advice: "Run flash sales. That's how you grow on Instagram."

I get it. The algorithm rewards urgency. Limited time! Only 3 left! Buy now or cry later! It works. It drives revenue. It also reduces a 45-day handcrafted textile to an impulse buy.

**Here's what flash sales actually do to handloom:**

They signal that the "real" price was always inflated. That the product was never worth the original amount. That you, the buyer, outsmarted the brand. It's a game that fast fashion plays because their margins allow it. Handloom margins don't.

**What we do instead:**

When a collection has only a few pieces left, we say exactly that. "3 bedcovers remaining. The next batch from this artisan group ships in August." No artificial scarcity -- real scarcity. Because handloom is slow. That's not a bug, it's the entire point.

**We show the math.** Our Banarasi Edit page breaks down the cost: 40% goes to the weaver family, 20% to raw silk, 15% to natural dyes, 15% to shipping and packaging, 10% to running SUTRA. When people see this, they stop asking for discounts.

**The result?** Our return rate is under 3%. Our repeat customer rate is 41%. People buy, they feel the fabric, they understand the value, and they come back.

No flash sale in the world builds that kind of loyalty.`,
